    "text": "Erdős Problem #112: declared status 'open'. Formalized: no. Let $k=k(n,m)$ be minimal such that any directed graph on $k$ vertices must contain either an independent set of size $n$ or a transitive tournament of size $m$. Determine $k(n,m)$. Current best: Zach Hunter has observed that\\[R(n,m) \\leq k(n,m)\\leq R(n,m,m),\\]which in particular proves the upper bound $k(n,m)\\leq 3^{n+2m}$. Prize: no. Tags: graph theory, ramsey theory.",
